{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112901/1153.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER FORECAST\nPartly cldudy and warmer today. Fair and\ncooler tonight, low 42. Cloudy, chance of\nrain Saturday. (Full report, Page A-2.)\nTemperatures Today\nMidnight 55 6an 57 11 an 60\n2 ana 55 8 ana 66 Noon 64\n4 ana\u2014s7 10 ana\u20146o 1 t>na 64\n105th Year. No. 333.\nSpace Control\nNext AF Aim,\nWhite Asserts\nChief of Staff Tells\nOs Three Actions\nTo Win Capability\nThe Chief of Staff of the\nAir Force said today that the\nnext step for his arm of the\nmilitary service is to achieve\nthe \u201ccapability to control\nspace.\u201d\nGen. Thomas D. White told\na National Press Club luncheon\nthat \u201cin the future whoever\nhas the capability to control\nspace will likewise possess the\ncapability to exert control of\nthe surface of the earth.\u201d\nGen. White said that as first\nsteps in America\u2019s drive to con\ntrol space, thfe Air Force has\ndone these three things:\n\"1. Transferred the first mis\nsile division to the Strategic\nAir Command.\n\u201c2. Transferred the responsi\nbility for the initial operational\ncapability phase of both the\nICBM and IRBM programs to\nthe Strategic Air Command.\n\"3. Directed the erltire re\nsources of the joint Air Force\ndepot at San Bernardino, Calif.,\nto be made available as required\nto support this effort.\u201d\nIssues Warning\nThe Air Force chief cautioned\nagainst the Nation's putting all\nits eggs in a basket labeled\ndefense.\n\u201cWe believe that our posses\nsion of strong offensive power\nwill make an enemy reluctant\nto. attack.\u201d Gen. White said.\n\u201cThe Maginot lane philosophy\nand Goering's claim that no\nallied bomber would reach Ber- 1\nlin are examples of the danger\nof excessive confidence in the\ndefense.\u201d\nGen. White emphasized that\ndefenses must be made strong,\n\u201cbut with enough money, ef\nfort and talent, we can main\ntain the first-rate offensive\npower that will make an enemy\nfear to strike.\u201d\nThe Nation's No. 1 airman\ntold his audience of about 430\nnewsmen and guests that his\nservice did not aspire to a mo\nnopoly in the missile field.\n\u201cSince missiles are becoming\nmore important to the national\nsecurity,\u201d he said, \u201cit is logical\nthat all military services should\nshare an interest in the develop\nment and use of missiles. How\never, it is important to note\nthe differences in interest\nclearly because there are\nmarked differences that show\nup in mission requirements j\nand in the matter of system I\ncompleteness.\n\"The point I want to make is\nthat in the context of the Air]\nForce\u2019s missions and combat\ntechnology, manned aircraft,\nunmanned systems and man\nned spacecraft join together in\ncompatible and complementary\nroles to form a functionally\ncomplete system.\u201d\nGen. White dealt at some\nlength with the Air Force\u2019s re\ncent probings into the lower\nfringes of space. He cited the\nrocket research plane X-2 as\nan early example and the X-15\nas a more recent type of ex\nperimental spacecraft.\nCites Integrated System\n\"I think it is interesting to\npoint out that in the develop\nment of this spacecraft, the air\nframe, the power plant, the\ncockpit and the pilot compose\narf integrated system.\u201d Gen.\nWhite said. \"A special pres\nsure suit has been designed for\nuse in conjunction with the\nX-15.\u201d\nThe X-15 spacesuit was\nbrought to the National Press\nClub ballroorp by the Air Force\nand was shown to the audience.\nOen. White defined the three\nprimary combat missions of\nhis branch of the service as\n\u201cto maintain a strong, long\nrange striking force, to conduct\nthe air defense of the United\nStates and to provide and\noperate practical air forces\nwherever they may be needed.\u201d\nHe estimated America\u2019s pres\nent capabilities in each of these\nfields as \u201creasonably adequate,\nparticularly as far as the of\nfense is concerned.\u201d\nCALL TODAY\nYOUR WEEK-END\nWANT ADS\nin\nSTAR\nCLASSIFIED\nNOW\nThe deadline tonight for\nwant ads to be published\nin the Saturday or Sunday\nStar is 10 o'clock by tele\nphone or 9 o\u2019clock at the\nbusiness counter in The\nStar lobby.\nCALL STERLING 3-5000\nPhone ST. 3-5000\nGEN THOMAS D. WHITE\nSeeks Control of Space\n\u2014Star Btaff Photo\n\nBaltimore lube\nTo Open Tonight\nTunnel Will Speed\nTraffic Past City\nBy ALEX R. PRESTON\nStir Stiff Correspondent\nBALTIMORE. Nov. 29\nMaryland\u2019s largest single en\ngineering\u2019 project\u2014the $l3O\nI million Baltimore Harbor Tun\nnel\u2014was dedicated today in\npreparation for its opening to\ntoll traffic at midnight.\nBeginning at 12:01 a.m. to\nmorrow, Washington-area mo-\nPicture on Page A-19\ntorists bound for the Army-\nNavy game ih Philadelphia or\nto other points North may, for\na fee of 40 cents, trim the driv\ning time through Baltimore\nfrom about qn hour to 12 min\nutes.\nTolls will be 60 cents for two\naxle trucks and 70 cents for\nthree-akle vehicles.\nGov. McKeldin of Maryland,\nin remarks prepared for de\nlivery at the dedication thii\nafternoon, warned that the\ntwin-tube tunnel is \u201cnot the\nsolution to Baltimore\u2019s notori\nous traffic congestion prob\nlem.\"\nHe praised workers on \u201cthis\ngreatest construction feat in\nMaryland\u2019s history\u2014from the\nmen who mixed the mortar to\nthe men who planned and\nsupervised the Job.\u201d\n\u201cN* Traffic Cure-All\u201d\n\u201cDespite the magnificence\nand utility value of this great\ntunnel, it is no cure-all for\nthe traffic troubles of the city,\u201d\nhe said.\n\u201cIt is true that the tunnel\ntransforms one of the most\ndifficult cities through which\nto drive to one of the easiest.\nBut I must remind you again\nthat Baltimore is not primarily\nI a city through which to pass.\nIt is a city in which to transact\nI business, manufacture and dis\ntribute goods, and a leading\nworld seaport.\n\u201cThe trade routes of the even\ngreater city of tomorrow must\nrun to and through the busi\nness heart of the city\u2014not\naway from it.\u201d\nThe 6,298-foot long tunnel\nand its more than 17 miles of\nsuperhighway approaches were\nthrown open to the public for\nfree inspection for about two\nhours this afternoon after the\ndedication.\nPraises Co-Operation\nBaltimore\u2019s Mayor Thomas\nD\u2019Alesandro said comletion of\nthe project, which connects the\nVanton and Fairfield shipyard\nareas beneath the Patapsco\nRiver, demonstrates \"again that\nthe State and city governments\ncan and do work together tri\nharmony for the good of the\ncommunity.\nOpening of the project will\nmake it the largest trench\ntype tunnel in the world. On\nNovember 1 the S6O million\ntunnel beneath Hampton\nRoads, connecting Norfolk and\nNewport News in Virginia, was\nopened to traffic. It enjoyed\nthe record as the \u201clargest\u201d up\nI until now.\nActual travel time through\nthe Baltimore city limits will\nbe about five minutes. A total\nof 1? minutes is required by\nmotorists from the time they\nleave the Baltimore-Washing\nton expressway for the tunnel\napproach, to the time they\nreach U. S. Route 40 at the\nother side of tpwn.\nOnly one stop\u2014at the toll\ngate\u2014is involved, compared\nwith at least 43 traffic light\nstops on the former route\nthrough the city.\nTwo Crash Victims\nFound in Mountain\nMARGARETVILLE. N. Y.,\nNov. (\u00a3*).\u2014rSearch parties have\nrecovered the bodies of two Air\nForce officers from wreckage of\ntheir jet plane which crashed\nWednesday in the rugged ter\nrain of Panther Mountain.\nThey were identified as Capt.\nRoy W. Schellhous, 37, of Rome,\nN..Y., the pilot, and Lt. John\nA. Hartzfeld, 27, of Luthers\nburg. Pa., a radar observer.\nA witness reported that the\nplane came down in flames It\nwas on a flight from Orlffiiaa\nAir Force baae at Rome.\nBerlin Christmas Fund\nBERLIN, Nov. 29 (i*P). The\nthree Western allied com\nmandants are donating $47,600\ni equivalent* for the West\nBerlin government to distribute\nat Christmas among the poor.\n\u00a9he Itoenina itaf\nV, y J V y WITH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION\nWASHINGTON, D. C., FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 29, 1957\u201460 .PAGES\nTunisia Makes\nAlgerian Plea\nIn U. N. Debale\nEnvoy to U. S. Asks\nFrance to Accept\nMediation Offer\nUNITED NATIONS, N. Y\u201e\nNov, 29 (JP).\u2014Tunisia appealed\nto France today to put aside\n\u201cnarrow nationalism\u201d and ac\ncept the Tunisian-Moroccan\noffer to mediate the' Algerian\ndispute.\nMongi Slim, t Tunisian Am\nbassador to Washington and\nthe United Nations, made the\nappeal in a debate on Algeria\nin the General Assembly\u2019s Po\nlitical Committee. He spoke\nout about the time Premier\nFelix Gaillard announced in\nParis the offer of the two for\nmer French protectorates had\nbeen rejected.\nHe read out the offer of good\noffices in 41gerian-French ane\ngotiations made in Rabat last\nweek by King Mohamed V of\nMorocco and President Habib\nBourguiba of Tunisia.\nOne Response Cited\nHe remarked that one of the\nparties in the case, the Algerian\nFront of 'National Liberation,\n\u201cresponded to that appeal in\nterms which permit every\nhope.\u201d\n\u201cMay we be able to meet a\nsimilar spirit and a like com\nprehension from the other\nparty in the case,\u201d said Mr.\nSlim. \u201cMay we be able to see\nFrench wisdom triumph\nover passion and a narrow na\ntionalism that is neither in the\ntrue French tradition nor in\nthe interest of France.\u201d\nFrench Foreign Minister\nChristian Pineau opened the\ndebate Wednesday. He plead\nled with delegates to steer clear\nof \u201cinternationalization of the\nAlgerian conflict\u201d and let\nFrance go on seeking a \u201cpeace\nful, democratic and just solu\ntion\u201d by crushing the rebellion\nand Introducing electoral re\nforms to benefit Algerian. Mos\nlems.\nStronger Resolution Seen\nIn a vague resolution adopted\nlast February 15,- the Assembly\nexpressed hope that \u201ca peace\nful, democratic and just solu\ntion\u201d would be found in con\nformity with U. N. Charter\nprinciples. Twenty-two African\nand Asian delegations revived\nthe issue in this session on\ngrounds no progress has been\nmade in that direction. Both\nArab and Western diplomatic\nsources expressed belief last\nnight that a stronger resolu\ntion will be adopted this time.;\nThe debate is expected to\nlast about 10 days.\nYesterday a joint Washing\nton statement from King Mo\nhamed and Secretary of State\nDulles said that in their talks\non Algeria the King expressed\nthe hope for a \u201cpeaceful solu\ntion through friendly nego\ntiations.\u201d Mr. Dulles also stated\nthe United States favored \"a\npeaceful, democratic and Just\nsolution.\u201d\nGaillard Rejects\nMediation Offer\nPARIS. Nov. 29 (<P). \u2014France\ntoday rejected the mediation\noffer of Morocco and Tunisia\nbut agreed to accept their help\nin seeking a cease-fire to end\nthe three-year nationalist re\nbellion in Algeria.\nThe French decision was an\nnounced by Premier Felix Gail\nlard in the National Assembly\nas he made a final plea for two\ngovernment bills which are in\ntended to give Algeria at least\npartial home rule once peace\nhas been restored there.\nThe bills\u2014one setting up a\nfederal form of government for\nthe territory's home affairs and\nthe other ruling on how elec\ntions should be organized to\ngive fair representation for\nboth Moslems and Europeans\u2014\nwere both made issues of con\nfidence in the three-week-old\nGaillard government.\nThey are expected to be\nvoted on later today.\nHoliday Story of Mirth.\nBegins in The Sunday Star\nAll that Is Inevitable, maddening and amus\ning about Christmas is brought to you in a 12-\npart holiday series, entitled \u201cMerry Christmas,\nMr. Baxter\u201d which begins in The Star this\nSunday.\nWritten by Edward Streeter (author of\n\u201cFather of the Bride\"), \u201cMerry Christmas, Mr.\nBaxter\" is the story of one man\u2019s frustrating and\namusing Christmas experiences, and how his\nlong-range holiday planning went out the win\ndow because he reckoned without this family.\nWhile you may laugh at our hero, you will\nrecognize the poignant, enjoyable aspects of his\nfamily situation as your own.\nDon\u2019t mbs a single entertaining installment\nof \u201cMerry Christmas, Mr. Baxter\u201d starting this\nSunday in The Star.\nPhone Sterling_3-5000 for home delivery.\n\nPresident at Farm, Shows\n\nContinued Fast Recovery\nWr 1 if I\n/k J jBl _\u25a0 igjL\nj ii mffii i\" jififp'' v\nTHE EISENHOWER GRlN\u2014President Eisen\nhower flashes a broad smile at photographers\nas he and Mrs. Eisenhower leave the White\nHouse by car this morning for their Gettysburg\nWoman Shot\nIn 'Roulette'\nCritically Hurt\nAt Dinner Party\nA Bethesda (Md.) woman\nwas critically wounded when a\nbullet from a .45 caliber re\nvolver ripped into her head\nduring a game of Russian\nroulette following Thanksgiv\ning dinner yesterday.\nMrs. Louise M. Lincoln, about\n48. 5033 Bradley boulevard, was\nclinging to life in Suburban\nHospital today after the shoot\ning last night at the home of\nher hosts, Mr. and Mrs Leslie A.\nTanner, at ,5 West Melrose\nstreet, Chevy Chase, near thej\ngrounds of the fashionable!\nChevy Chase Club. Montgomery\nCounty Police said.\nDetective Lt. John Leahy said\nMrs. Lincoln was wounded in\nthe kitchen of the Chevy Chase\nhome where she, the Tanners\nand two oiher friends were\nhaving a drink after wishing\nthe dinner dishes about 8:30\np.m.\nMother Upstairs\nThe Tanners live in the\nMelrose street home of Mrs.\nTanner\u2019s invalid mother. Mrs.\nAlexander McClure Ashley, who\nwas upstairs at the time.\nLt. Leahy said Mrs. Lincoln,!\nthe Tanners and Jesse Ricketts,\nwho lives in another apart-!\nment at the Bradley boulevard\naddress, and Herbert William\nBankcy. 59, a male nurse and\nhandyman who lives at the\nChevy Chase home, were in\nthe kitchen when the shooting\noccurred.\nMr. Tanner got the revolver\nfrom the dining room to show\nhis guests. Lt. Leahy said.\nThere was one bullet in it\nand the other five chambers\nwere empty, he said.\nMrs. Lincoln put the revolver j\nSee ROULETTE, Pace A-10\n'Boner 'on NATO Trip\nAnnouncement Seen\nIndications Are That Eisenhower\nShould Have Been Consulted\nIt looks as though some of President Eisenhower\u2019s associ\nates may have pulled a \u201cboo-boo\u201d in assuming that his ill\nness would prevent his attendance at the NATO summit\nmeeting in Paris December 16.\nIndications were that this was one time the President\nhimself should have been consulted on a decision taken by\nhis associates\u2014and that hei\nmay not have been.\nWithin a couple of hours after\ndisclosure Tuesday afternoon\nthat Mr. Eisenhower had sut\nfered on Monday an occlusion\nof a small cerebral branch ar\ntery, newsmen at the White\nHouse were informed:\n\u201cThe State-Department, after\nconsultation with the White\nHouse, has just made this an\nnouncement:\n\u201cIt is to be assumed that\nPresident Eisenhower will not\nattend the NATO meeting in\nDecember. Mr. (Paul Henri)\nSpaak, the Secretary General,\nhas been asked by us to ascer\ntain from other members (of\nNATO) how they wish this\nmeeting to be dealt with in the\nlight of this circumstance.\u201d\nNo Definite Declaration\nNo one at the White House\never said publicly and definitely\nthat the President would not\n|go to the Paris meeting.\nBut the general assumption,\non the basis of the Tuesday\nafternoon statement, was that\nVice President Nixon would\nsubstitute for the President.\nAnd that this was no idle\nspeculation seemed obvious\nwhen Mr. Spaak announced in\nParis early yesterday that the\nNATO council had \u201clearned\nwith satisfaction\u201d that Mr\nNixon would head the Ameri\ncan delegation.\nWas President Consulted?\nThe Spaak announcement\nfrom Paris was hardly in print\nbefore White House Press Sec\nretary James C. Hagerty an\nnounced that the President had\nlooked forward to attending the\nNATO meeting, and \u201chis doc\ntors will decide later whether he\ncan make the trip.\u201d\nThe announcement added\nSuhrawardy Hurt\nBy Demonstrators\nKARACHI. Pakistan. Nov. 29\n(rP).\u2014Former Prime Minister\nHussein Suhrawardy and his\nchauffeur were injured today\nwhen a crowd of about 200.000\nmobbed them outside the Na\ntional Assembly Building.\nMounted police rushed to the\nrescue and got Mr. Suhrawardy\naway Apparently neither was\ninjured seriously. The car was\nseverely damaged.\nThe crowd was demonstrating\nin support of Prime Minister\nIsmail Chundrlgar\u2019s proposal\nthat elections be held under a\nseparate polls system for Mos\nlems. Hindus and Christians.\nMr. Suhrawardy, leader of the\nopposition, has opposed the\nelection change.\nfarm. The car is not the President\u2019s usual\nlimousine, but it Mrs. Eisenhower\u2019s personal\nWhite House car.\u2014Star Staff Photo oy Paul\nSehmick.\nI\nthat Mr. Nixon would head the\ndelegation \u201cif the President\nfinds he cannot go\u201d\u2014apparent\nly still a big \u201cif.\u201d\nMr. Eisenhower had been con\nsulted on the actions taken bv\nthis Government during his 111- j\nness with resfiect to the NATO\nmeeting\nOne reporter asked: \u201cHa'\nanybody discussed with the\nPresident since Monday this\nsuggestion that he might or\nmight not be able to go to Paris\n\u2014in exactly those terms?\u2019\u2019 Mr.\n'Hagerty replied, \u201cI don\u2019t\nj know.\u201d\nThe press secretary made it\nclear that Mr. Elsenhower did\napprove his announcement of\nyesterday that leaves open the\npossibility that he still might\ngo to the NATO meeting.\nQuestions flew thick and fast\nto Mr. Hagerty about whether\nWednesday both he and Vice\nPresident Nixon had empha\nsized that the decision on\nAmerican representation at the\nNATO session remains for de\ncision by the President, despite\napparently firm news reports\nfrom Paris that Mr. Nixon\nwould go to the meeting in the\nPresident's place.\nAt a later news conference,\nMr. Hagerty was asked\u2014in the\nlight of his earlier statement\nthat he did not know whether\nanybody had discussed the\nNATO attendance matter \u00bb\\h\nthe President since Monday\u2014\nwhen the President made the\nSee MIXUP. Page A-10\nDowntownAreaJommed\nWith Shopping Crowds\nChristmas shopping crowds\ndescended on downtown Wash\nington today, snarling traffic\nin some spots, filling parking\nlots and jamming store gift\ncounters.\nWith the Thanksgiving tur\nkey hardly cold, the rush sig\nnaled the opening of the big\nChristmas season. Merchants\nwere well pleased at the size\nof the crowds and reported the\nheaviest activity in children's\ndepartments.\nMetropolitan police had 58\nextra men gathered from all\nprecincts on traffic duty in\ndowntown streets. But even\nthey had trouble moving cars\nrapidly through Jammed inter\nsections and parking lot en\ntrances.\nAdding to the crowds were\nthousands of Government work\ners taking the day off and\nschool children who won\u2019t re-\nMetropolitan\nEdition\nNew York Markets, Page A-17\nHorn. Delivered: &88\nU.S. Will Grant\n2 Hall Holidays\n-4 V\nWork to End Early\nOn 24th and 31st\nBy JOSEPH YOUNG\nGovernment employes will\nreceive half-day holidays on\nthe days before Christmas and\nNew Year\u2019s.\nThat\u2019s the word of White\nHouse officials who are now\ndrafting a presidential execu\ntive order to this effect that\nwill be issued by President Ei\ni senhower.\nEmployes will be excused at\nnoon on Tuesday, December\n24. and Tuesday, December 31,\nwithout charge to their annual\nleave.\nIn years when the holidays\nfell on the first of the week\nor on the last work day of the\nweek, employes frequently were\ngiven an entire extra day's\nholiday for them to get in some\nextra travel time, etc. But when\nthe holidays fall in the middle\nof the week, the custom usually\nhas been to give employes a\nhalf-holiday on the preceding\nday.\nMt. Etna Erupts Again,\nNo Danger Imminent\nCATANIA, Sicily, Nov. 29\nUP).\u2014 Etna, Sicily\u2019s on-agian,\noff-agaln volcano, is on again.\nVulcanologists at nearby Zaf\nferana reported that Europe's\nmost active volcano is erupting\nwith an explosion about every\n10 minutes.\nVulcanologists emphasized\nthat there is no immediate dan\nger from this eruption.\nThey said ashes from the ex\nplosion were falling back into\nthe crater, but that a tongue of\nlava had moved about 1,000 feet\ndown the northeast slope.\nturn to classes until Monday.\nThe weather was warm and\ndry after a morning shower.\nIt was to turn cooler tonight\nand tomorrow.\nSome parking lots were filled\nwell before noon and operators\ndirected drivers to other lots\nand garages.\nThe story was much the same\nin suburban shopping centers.\nStores were crowded minutes\nafter opening their doors.\nThe day after Thanksgiving\ntraditionally is a big shopping\nday Most stores will remain\nopen until 9 o'clock tonight.\nPolice had their hands full\nnot only with traffic but with\na seasonal growth of petty\ncrime. An extra 25 plainclothes,\nmen will be detailed to the\ndowntown area to look for\nshoplifters and purse snatch\ners. No leaves will be granted\npolicemen from December 10\nuntil after Christmas.\n5 CENTS\nStay May\nLast Into\nNext Week\nBy GARNETT D. HORNER\nPresident Eisenhower, sur\nprising everybody with how fast\nhe is getting well, drove to hla\nGettysburg farm today for fur\nther recuperation.\nMr. and Mrs. Eisenhower left\nthe White House this morning\nat 10:45 and reached their farm\nat 12:52 p.m. without incident.\nThe Gettysburg trip was\nadditional evidence of the rapid\nrecovery the President drama\ntized by escorting Mrs. Eisen\nhower to Thanksgiving church\nservices yesterday.\nMr. Eisenhower\u2019s \u201cprogress\ncontinues to be excellent,\u201d his\npersonal physician, Maj. Gen.\nHoward M. Snyder, reported at\n8:30 a.m. todav.\nWijite House Press Secretary\nJames C. Hagerty said the\nPresident went to sleep about\n8 o\u2019clock last night and slept\nalmost continuously until 6\no\u2019clock this morning.\nDiscusses Program\nThe President spent a half\nhour with Sherman Adams, his\ntop assistant, and Brig. Gen.\nAndrew S. Goodpaster, staff\nsecretary, discussing \u201ccertain\nphases of the legislative pro\ngram,\u201d Mr. Hagerty told re\nporters.\nHe also signed 11 documents\nand initialed another. The doc\numents concerned civil aero\nnautics. tariff and other mat\nters, Mr. Hagerty said. Their\nexact nature will be made pub\nlic. he said, after the various\nexecutive agencies involved\nhave been informed.\nNeither NATO nor the Fed\neral budget came up for dis\ncussion this morning during ths\nPresident\u2019s half-hour confer\nence in the White House livln*\nroom near his bedroom, Mr.\nHagerty said.\nMr. Adams and Gen. Good\npastor reported the President\nis \"looking very well.\u201d\nMany well-wishing messages\nhave been received from heads\nof state and governments since\nthe President fell ill. Mr. Hag\nerty said, but the White House\npolicy is not to make them\npublic for fear of leaving one\noff the list.\nMany Send Prayers\nThe President also has re\nceived a great deal of corre\nspondence from well-wishers in\nthe United States, many of\nwhom sent their prayers for a\nspeedy recovery.\nVice President Nixon came to\nthe White House for the third\nstraight day. He arrived at\n9:45 a.m.\nVice President Nixon spent\nthe morning conferring with\nMr. Adams on preparations for\nnext Monday\u2019s cabinet meeting\nand the December 3 Whit*\nHouse conference with legisla\ntive leaders.\nAssociate Press Secretary Mrs.\nAnne Wheaton said the Vice\nPresident planned to stay at\nthe White House until about\nContinued on Page A-10, Col. 1\nRadford Arrives\nFor Formosa Visit\nTAIPEI, Nov. 29 OP).\u2014Ad\nmiral Arthur W. Radford\n(retired), former chairman of\nthe United States Joint Chiefs\nof Staff arrived here with his\nwife tonight from Manilla for\na three-day visit to Formosa.\nAt the airport to welcome\nthem were Mme. Chiang Kai-\nShek. Premier O. K. Yul and\nothers.\nThey are the house guests\nof President and Mme. Chiang\nKai-Shek.\nAdmiral Radford is reportedly\ninterested in surveying the\nprospects of investments in\nFormosa paper mills for one\nof the companies he represents.\nBEAR HUNT TAKES\nCOURAGE AND DOG\nREAR HUNTING requires stamina\nand courage. Charles Corell de\nscribes a hunt in the Virginia moun\ntains in which Old Trey, a hound\not rare courage, led a pack against\none beor. The story is on Pagt C-4.\nHELPFUL TIPS to the men an\nho* to make the right choice tor\nmilady this are giren\nby Eleni on Poge $-2.\nGuide for Readers\nAmuse'ts A 24 25 Feature Page 6-14\nlusmess ond Leisure Sports C-4\nFinance A-16-17 Lott, Found. A-3\nClassified C-S-12 Obituary A-22\nComics $-16-17 Sports C-l-4\nCrossword $-16 TV-Rodio 1-15\nEditorial A-14 Woman's\nEdit'l Articles A-15 Section 1-16\nHave The Star Delivered to\nYour Home Doily and Sunday\nDial Sterling 3-5000","height":"28641","width":"18066"}}
